            "id": "35e5032407d14bce80222",
            "questionText": "Consider a block of mass $!$m = 2\\text{ kg}$!$ attached to a spring with a spring constant $!$k = 50\\text{ N/m}$!$ on a horizontal surface with a coefficient of dynamic friction $!$\\mu_d = 0.3$!$. The spring is initially compressed by $!$x_0 = 0.5\\text{ m}$!$ from its equilibrium position and then released. Determine the distance the block travels before it comes to a complete stop due to the combined forces of the spring and friction. Assume that the block starts moving immediately upon release.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "b068f94a917644d88cceb",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the proper formula for the elastic potential energy stored in a compressed spring. Which of the following represents the correct formula?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "619a9763-10d2-48a6-a060-de4db6ea3c0a"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$U = kx$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$U = \\frac{1}{2}kx^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$U = kx^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "f46729a11aa04305b3b5a",
                    "stepText": "Now, use the formula from the previous step to calculate the initial energy stored in the spring when it is compressed by $!$0.5$!$ m with a spring constant of $!$50$!$ N/m.",
