        {
            "id": "9e823c9616c54fceb31a8",
            "questionText": "An astronaut with a mass of $!$m_0 = 100 \\text{ kg}$!$ is performing a spacewalk and accidentally collides with a piece of debris with a mass of $!$m_d = 5 \\text{ kg}$!$. Before the collision, the astronaut is stationary relative to the ISS, and the debris is moving at a velocity of $!$v_d = 3 \\text{ m/s}$!$ towards her. The collision is partially inelastic, with a coefficient of restitution of $!$e = 0.6$!$. Calculate the kinetic energy lost during the collision. (Note: The coefficient of restitution is the ratio of the relative speed of the two objects after the collision to the relative speed before the collision. For an elastic collision, the coefficient of restitution is 1.)",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "768044d458544858a4a3f",
                    "stepText": "Let's begin by selecting the formula that expresses the principle of momentum conservation. Which of the following formulas best represents that the total momentum before and after the collision remains constant?",
